Naw homie.  You don't use an LLC to buy your primary residence (or a vacation residence).  The purpose of an LLC is to protect your personal assets (like your primary residence) from liability when you get sued.  Keeping your private home in an LLC means you don't qualify for a number of tax breaks and pay a higher interest rate.  You keep your investment properties in LLCs and your residence in your own name.  

&#x200B;

I realize people are buying cash, but with essentially 0% interest, everyone that can is taking on mortgage debt.  What you are arguing for is just retarded financial planning. 

&#x200B;

People buy real estate cash for only one reason: the IRS is not allowed to investigate the source of funds used for real estate transactions.  These are special rules for real estate that are different from EVERY OTHER TRANSACTION. Real estate doesn't get investigated for drug money/offshore money laundering the same way that stocks, bonds, commodities, hell even putting money into a savings account does. That gap in regulation created this flow of cash.

You can't split single family homes from apartments when cities exist.  Most families live in apartments, but those apartments can be purchased rather than just rented.  I think the better move would be to simply apply the same rules for real estate that the IRS uses for EVERY OTHER TRANSACTION.  Real estate doesn't get investigated for drug money/offshore money laundering the same way that stocks, bonds, commodities, hell even putting money into a savings account does.  That gap in regulation created this problem.  

&#x200B;

We know that the Taliban purchased US real estate with heroin dollars to aid in the 9/11 bombings because of this loophole, and we did nothing to close it.
